import io

r = requests.get('http://www.pythonchallenge.com/pc/def/channel.zip')

‚ÄúCollect the comments.‚Äù Comments?

Google tells me that in a ZIP file, each file can have a ‚Äúcomment‚Äù. OK. Fine.

**Input:**
```python
n = b'90052'
c = b''
while True:
    c += zf.NameToInfo['%d.txt' % int(n)].comment
    with zf.open('%d.txt' % int(n)) as f:
        data = f.read()
        n = data.rpartition(b' ')[2]
    if not n.isdigit():
        print('nothing is not digit!', data, n)
        break

```

Clicking on the bull leads to this text page, <http://www.pythonchallenge.com/pc/return/sequence.txt>:

> a = [1, 11, 21, 1211, 111221,

Looking at the array, I notice that each element has a length of a multiple of 2 (except for the first element). How does the next element come from the previous one?

‚Ä¶‚Ä¶

OK, I think I get it. After many times of trial and error, I found out that 11 means the previous term has ‚Äúone 1‚Äù, 21 means there are ‚Äútwo 1s‚Äù, 1211 means there are ‚Äúone 2, one 1‚Äù and so on.

Googling this sequence, it is actually called the ‚ÄúLook-and-say sequence‚Äù. ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Look-and-say_sequence), [OEIS](https://oeis.org/A005150)) So, OK. This is a math problem. Let‚Äôs do it with Python.

**Input:**
```python
a = '1'
for i in range(1, 31):
    b = ''
    c = 1
    for j in range(1, len(a)):
        if a[j] != a[j-1]:
            b += '%d%s' % (c, a[j-1])
            c = 1
        else:
            c += 1
    b += '%d%s' % (c, a[-1])
    a = b
    # print('a[%d]: %s' % (i, a))
    print('len(a[%d]): %d' % (i, len(a)))
```
